others, notably
Syria. Peace talks begin this
month, and that

20:44.310 --> 20:48.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is the next big challenge we
face on whether
we can really do business with
Iran or not.

20:48.581 --> 20:50.483 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And I want to ask
you all about
that.

20:50.516 --> 20:54.687 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Ray Takeyh, what about this
decision
to swap these Iranian-Americans
in prison

20:54.720 --> 20:56.689 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for the Iranians in the U.S.?

20:56.722 --> 20:59.625 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAY TAKEYH, Former State
Department Official:
The issue of American hostages
always exercises

20:59.658 --> 21:03.996 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
an emotive burden, emotional
burden on any
U.S. president.

21:04.029 --> 21:11.070 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it did so with Ronald Reagan
when he essentially
traded arms for American
hostages in Lebanon.

21:11.103 --> 21:16.942 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think, as this deal unfolds,
you begin to
see the humanitarian aspects of
it and the

21:16.976 --> 21:20.146 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
possible emotional burden it
imposes on the
president.

21:20.179 --> 21:24.183 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But as you step back from it, in
hindsight,
you begin to see the problematic
aspects of

21:24.216 --> 21:29.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it, which I think we all alluded
to. For one
thing, it violates the
administration's own

21:29.121 --> 21:33.292 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
red line. They had suggested
that all these
prisoners have to be released
immediately,

21:33.325 --> 21:37.463 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
which is another way of saying
unconditionally.
And, essentially, then you see a
trade take

21:37.496 --> 21:39.398 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
place.

21:39.431 --> 21:44.637 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, also, money changed hands.
So the components
of a deal are problematic, but
the humanitarian

21:44.670 --> 21:46.172 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
aspect of it are quite American.

21:46.205 --> 21:48.073 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You are saying
money changed
hands over these prisoners?

21:48.107 --> 21:52.311 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAY TAKEYH: Well, there is a
report of $1.7
billion going into some accounts
that Iran

21:52.344 --> 21:56.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
had going back to shah's time
because of the
disputed -- because of the
military sales

21:56.815 --> 21:58.851 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and contracts and so forth.

21:58.884 --> 22:03.956 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that could be another aspect
of this deal.
But even if you just look at it
from a prisoner-to-citizen

22:03.989 --> 22:08.627 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hostage swap, it has problematic
aspects to
it, but you have to juxtapose
that to the

22:08.661 --> 22:10.429 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
humanitarian aspects of it.

22:10.462 --> 22:16.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: What does it say,
Karim, about
the balance of power in Tehran,
about -- you

22:16.202 --> 22:22.007 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
know, we are told there is the
very conservative
faction and the more moderate
faction. Whatever

22:22.041 --> 22:27.179 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
-- however it is described, what
does it say
about the power balance there?

22:27.213 --> 22:32.718 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Well, I think
we can't underestimate
the Iranian civil society and
the vast majority

22:32.751 --> 22:37.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Iran's 80 million population
that is very
eager for change and
reconciliation with the

22:37.623 --> 22:39.425 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
outside world.

22:39.458 --> 22:43.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At the same time, we shouldn't
underestimate
the forces of darkness in Iran,
the supreme

22:43.429 --> 22:48.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leader of the Revolutionary
Guards, who are
deeply entrenched. They haven't
gone anywhere.

22:48.467 --> 22:54.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And they actually thrive in
isolation. Rapprochement
with the United States,
international economic

22:54.139 --> 22:57.643 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
integration would be more of a
threat to them
than continued hostilities.

22:57.676 --> 22:59.878 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, I think that fight will
continue in Iran.

22:59.912 --> 23:02.281 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Regardless of
this new deal.

23:02.314 --> 23:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Well, let me pick up on that,
because, Reuel
Gerecht, some people were
surprised that this

23:07.253 --> 23:13.826 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
nuclear deal was implemented as
quickly as
it was. How do you read that?
Why did Iran

23:13.859 --> 23:19.265 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
move as relatively quickly as
they did? Or
do you not see it as a
relatively quick implementation?

23:19.298 --> 23:23.235 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REUEL MARC GERECHT: No, I think
they moved
quickly. I think people expected
implementation

23:23.269 --> 23:29.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
day to be later, even as late,
say, as July.
They want the money. I mean, I
think that's

23:29.108 --> 23:31.076 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
pretty clear.

23:31.110 --> 23:37.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The price of oil keeps dropping.
They need
the money desperately. They have
-- I mean,

23:37.683 --> 23:42.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they have to afford Syria, the
war in Syria.
They have to -- they spend a lot
of money

23:42.588 --> 23:45.157 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in Iraq. They spend some money
in Yemen.

23:45.190 --> 23:51.897 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think you have seen an
accentuation of what
you might call Iranian
imperialism and sectarian

23:51.930 --> 23:56.669 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
warfare, and they have to
support that. And
then there are also the domestic
needs. I

23:56.702 --> 24:02.775 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
think one needs to be very
careful about paring
moderates and hard-liners in
Iran. I think,

24:02.808 --> 24:06.378 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on this issue, they are marching
more or less
in synch.

24:06.412 --> 24:10.916 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Robin Wright,
how do you
see that divide or split as it
exists in Tehran?

24:10.949 --> 24:14.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN WRIGHT: Well, it's a very
profound split,
and it's really over the future
course of

24:14.286 --> 24:19.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the revolution. Is the country,
first and
foremost, an Islamic State, or
is it a modern

24:19.558 --> 24:21.327 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
republic?

24:21.360 --> 24:24.430 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That has been the issue that has
been debated
since the very beginning of the
revolution.

24:24.463 --> 24:28.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it will play out again next
month when
Iranians go to the polls. And I
think one

24:28.133 --> 24:32.871 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of the reasons in terms of the
timing of when
the nuclear deal and the
prisoners were released

24:32.905 --> 24:37.476 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
has a lot to do with public
perception at
home, momentum to show that
President Rouhani

24:37.509 --> 24:39.912 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
has been more effective than
some of the hard-liners.

24:39.945 --> 24:44.149 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But we have to remember this is
an opening
to the outside world, but it is
not an opening

24:44.183 --> 24:50.723 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inside the country. Today, the
Iranian government,
Guardian Council, which vets all
candidates,

24:50.756 --> 24:55.427 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disqualified over 60 percent of
the candidates
who want to run for Parliament
next month.

24:55.461 --> 24:57.296 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
This is still a very closed
society.

24:57.329 --> 25:03.569 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we shouldn't have any
illusions that these
very two important steps are
going to change

25:03.602 --> 25:05.404 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the political dynamics
significantly.

25:05.437 --> 25:11.176 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, I mean,
that gets me
to the question I wanted to ask
next, Ray

25:11.210 --> 25:17.049 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Takeyh. Do we expect Iran to
change as a result
of this, a nuclear deal, the
release of these

25:17.082 --> 25:18.851 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
prisoners, and the rest of it?

25:18.884 --> 25:21.086 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
RAY TAKEYH: I think that
certainly, as Karim
was saying, the fear of the
supreme leader

25:21.120 --> 25:27.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and those around him, that this
particular
opening can presage a moderation
of Iran and

25:27.459 --> 25:29.395 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
modernization of its politics.

25:29.428 --> 25:32.998 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
this is why they are
disqualifying the people
that they are. This is why you
have an extraordinary

25:33.031 --> 25:37.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
degree of repression inside the
country today,
because the fear that they have
is an opening

25:37.636 --> 25:41.974 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will essentially subvert the
revolution, because
they understand as well as
anyone the dynamics

25:42.007 --> 25:45.978 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
of their society and the
demographics of their
society. And they essentially
want to close

25:46.011 --> 25:47.846 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
off those paths.

25:47.880 --> 25:52.017 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, Karim, what
do we look
for next? I mean, does Iran
change its position

25:52.050 --> 25:56.922 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
on Syria? I mean, Robin
mentioned Syria. I
mean, they are involved in so
many different

25:56.955 --> 26:02.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
pieces of the very messy puzzle
in the Middle
East right now. What do we
expect to change,

26:02.861 --> 26:04.663 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
if anything?

26:04.696 --> 26:07.399 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: I don't think
Iran's external
policies are going to change.
And at least

26:07.433 --> 26:12.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the near term, I think there
is a valid
concern that they will become
even more repressive

26:12.037 --> 26:17.810 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
domestically to send a signal to
their population,
don't confuse our external
flexibility for

26:17.843 --> 26:19.611 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
internal weakness.

26:19.645 --> 26:24.416 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I think that these momentous
peace deals
in the Middle East, the
momentous events in

26:24.450 --> 26:28.954 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the Middle East really have to
be judged over
a period of many years. And I
think that trying

26:28.987 --> 26:34.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to crack open Iran, the fact
that it's Iranian
civil society and modern forces
who are happy

26:34.526 --> 26:39.631 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about this nuclear deal and the
hard-liners
who are concerned, I think it
increases the

26:39.665 --> 26:43.602 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
chances, even if small, about
the prospects
for change in Iran.

26:43.635 --> 26:46.738 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
the prospects
for change, Reuel Gerecht?

26:46.772 --> 26:50.342 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
REUEL MARC GERECHT: I think it
is going to
get worse.

26:50.375 --> 26:55.113 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think this nuclear deal is
likely to do
the opposite of what President
Obama hopes

26:55.147 --> 27:00.786 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it will do. I think the Iranians
will become
more aggressive in the region.
And I think,

27:00.819 --> 27:03.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
domestically, they will hit very
hard.

27:03.388 --> 27:05.123 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why?

27:05.157 --> 27:08.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REUEL MARC GERECHT: Because, as
Karim and
Ray, said, I think the supreme
leader, the

27:08.494 --> 27:13.031 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Revolutionary Guard Corps and
many others
really do feel the penetration
of a Western

27:13.065 --> 27:17.803 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
wedge, that the Western
businessmen come,
et cetera, et cetera. They are
bringing the

27:17.836 --> 27:20.973 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
plague of Western culture and
the whole regime
will start to unravel.

27:21.006 --> 27:24.076 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, are you
saying, on balance,
the nuclear deal and the
prisoner release

27:24.109 --> 27:26.011 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
were a bad idea?

27:26.044 --> 27:30.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
REUEL MARC GERECHT: Yes. I
think, on balance,
if your objective is to stop
them from developing

27:30.215 --> 27:34.319 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a nuclear weapon permanently,
the nuclear
deal is certainly not going to
do that.

27:34.353 --> 27:40.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What it does at best is kick
down the road
eight to 10 years this question
of the nuclear

27:40.792 --> 27:42.694 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
-- development of a nuclear
weapon, at best.

27:42.728 --> 27:44.630 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How do you see
the future Iran?

27:44.663 --> 27:48.567 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ROBIN WRIGHT: Well, I actually
think the nuclear
deal was a very important step
and that it

27:48.600 --> 27:53.338 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
takes the danger of a nuclear
weapon off the
table for a lot longer than
eight to 10 years,

27:53.372 --> 27:57.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
25 years, in some cases, on some
of the most
important issues, and longer,
because Iran

27:57.643 --> 27:59.411 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
has to sign an agreement.

27:59.444 --> 28:03.015 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And if it violates that
agreement any time,
even after 25 years, it's liable
for military

28:03.048 --> 28:08.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
action. The military option is
not off the
table. It is off the table for
now. But this

28:08.387 --> 28:12.891 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
is still a revolutionary
society. And -- but
it does have interests.

28:12.925 --> 28:17.229 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And when it comes to interests,
self-interests,
Iran has taken some practical
steps over the

28:17.262 --> 28:21.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
last week. The big question is,
is it willing
to take more? And it will face a
lot of tests

28:21.833 --> 28:27.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in -- particularly across the
region. Can
it -- is it willing to walk away
from President

28:27.773 --> 28:32.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Assad in the name of peace and
stopping the
Islamic State, which has gotten
as close as

28:32.811 --> 28:34.513 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
25 miles from the Iranian
border?

28:34.546 --> 28:39.518 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They are afraid of it too. Can
they solve
-- are they willing to tolerate
some kind

28:39.551 --> 28:44.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of peace arrangement in Yemen?
What is going
to happen in Iraq? There are
places that we

28:44.523 --> 28:49.494 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
actually have common interests
with the Iranians
these days, which is a far cry
from the way

28:49.528 --> 28:51.096 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
it's been for most of the last
40 years.

28:51.129 --> 28:54.299 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Ray Takeyh, do
you anything
positive coming out of this?

28:54.333 --> 28:59.237 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAY TAKEYH: Well, there is a
contest playing
itself out in Iran, two visions.
They are

28:59.271 --> 29:01.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
both impractical.

29:01.073 --> 29:04.309 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One is a vision of Ali Khamenei,
namely, Iran
can shield itself from external
influences,

29:04.343 --> 29:09.915 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can develop its local economy
and regional
economy as a means of economic
growth, trade

29:09.948 --> 29:14.753 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with Iraq, Afghanistan, Central
Asia, and
it doesn't require the Western
commerce.

29:14.786 --> 29:18.957 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And there is Hassan Rouhani's
vision, namely,
that we can do a sort of a China
model, have

29:18.991 --> 29:24.796 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
commerce without democracy. They
both are
impractical visions and neither
one can succeed.

29:24.830 --> 29:28.333 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Iran cannot be self-sufficient,
nor can it
essentially insulate itself from
outside influence.

29:28.367 --> 29:33.205 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The Islamic Republic today feels
like the
Soviet Union of the 1970s, a
stagnant bureaucratic

29:33.238 --> 29:38.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
state incapable of reforming
itself and presaging
its probable implosion at some
point.

29:38.310 --> 29:40.045 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: But you're saying
that is going
to change?

29:40.078 --> 29:42.047 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RAY TAKEYH: I think that's a
good thing. It's
probably...

29:42.080 --> 29:43.849 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

29:43.882 --> 29:45.984 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RAY TAKEYH: Now, I don't know
when that is
going to happen, but Islamic
Republic cannot

29:46.018 --> 29:49.021 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
reform itself. It's too wedded
to its ideology
verities to do so.

29:49.054 --> 29:53.959 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On balance,
Karim, a good move
over the weekend, what the
Iranians did, or

29:53.992 --> 29:54.660 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
not?

29:54.693 --> 29:56.461 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: I think so.

29:56.495 --> 29:58.697 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You know, when you are in this
business, if
are you opposed to something,
you have to

29:58.730 --> 30:02.901 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
propose a better alternative.
And I think
that we're hard-pressed to come
up with a

30:02.934 --> 30:05.804 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
better alternative, and we have
to see what
happens.

30:05.837 --> 30:09.508 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, we will all
be watching.
And I know the four of you,
nobody watching

30:09.541 --> 30:15.681 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
closer than you, Ray Takeyh,
Karim Sadjadpour,
Robin Wright, Reuel Gerecht, we
thank you.

30:15.714 --> 30:20.185 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
REUEL MARC GERECHT: Pleasure.

30:20.218 --> 30:25.791 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
KARIM SADJADPOUR: Thank you,
Judy.

